<p>Calendars are for events, task managers are for tasks, notes apps are for details. Thatâ€™s a widely accepted principle. If you are using the traditional version of each of these and youâ€™re happy with the way itâ€™s working, then stop there! Thatâ€™s all you need.</p>
<p>Because Iâ€™m tracking tasks bare-bones style in my notes app, anything time sensitive is manually placed into my calendar. Repeating tasks become either events (if theyâ€™re time sensitive) or reminders.</p>
<p>Tasks that need doing <em>sometime</em> in order to move a project along go in my plain text task file, tagged with @1, @2, @3, or @4 depending on whether I plan to do them this week, this month, next month, or 3+ months. What go on the calendar are time blocks for working on a project, <em>not</em> the project tasks themselves.</p>
<p>It is possible to run everything from your notes, Bullet Journal style, with a text or paper calendar and future log. People have done variations on this for centuries. Iâ€™m choosing the convenience of a digital calendar, but itâ€™s good to know I donâ€™t <em>need</em> need it.</p>
<h3 id="choosing-a-calendar-app">Choosing a calendar app</h3>
<p>It doesnâ€™t matter what kind of calendar you choose if you have the discipline to use it properly.</p>
<p>Going old school with paper or a plain text list is fine, as long as you keep it up to date, check it daily (hourly, if necessary), and donâ€™t need automated reminders. As hard core plain-text-analog as I might seem sometimes, Iâ€™m no longer willing to follow <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/108-workflowy-text-calendar">this approach</a> on its own.</p>
